<br>
Arbitrary Numbers: ( Easier Math)<br>
<br>
Caster_01 casts 100 spells in 100 minutes<br>
Caster_01 fizzles 6 spells<br>
Caster_01 Completes 94 casts successfully<br>
<br>
Bard_01 casts 3 songs every minute for 100 minutes<br>
Bard_01 fizzles 18 songs<br>
Bard_01 Completes 282 casts successfully<br>
<br>
This is based on the 6% fizzle rate.  But in reality it is flawed.  For just using the above data a bard is casting 3x more than the caster.  It might be more in line if a 2% fizzle rate in the above scenario.  Then the bard and the caster should fizzle the same amount of time in the same amount of time, plus or minus.<br>
<br>
Having hard data between casters and bards for total spells cast, total sampling time, and total fizzles would be required to get the proper proportional fizzle rate for bards.<br>
<br>
At present, without being able to use Metronome, a 65 chanter doing an ldon might fizzle 10 spells the entire time, where as I miss AT LEAST one note EVERY PULL.  And Metronome sounds like I'll still miss at least one note every other pull, for a whopping 45 aa points.  And this is called balanced!<br>
<br>
